%S A397826 2,3,5,7,9,11,13,4,17,8,19,6,23,10,29,14,15,16,21,25,27,20,31,33,26,
%T A397826 35,37,12,41,39,22,43,47,28,53,55,32,49,34,59,51,61,38,67,45,71,18,65,
%U A397826 73,77,40,79,57,83,24,85,69,89,36,91,75,44,81,95,46,97,50
%N A397826 a(1) = 2; for n > 1, a(n) is the smallest unused number greater than 2 placed on a hexagon spiral that is coprime with any earlier term that is adjacent to it on the spiral.
%C A397826 A variation of A363938: in this sequence the smallest term is 2. Like A363938 the terms are concentrated along four lines although here the top two lines show periods of convergence - see the attached images. The topmost line contains all the primes along with other numbers with relatively few prime factors.
%C A397826 It is conjectured the sequence contains all positive numbers.
%H A397826 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A397826/b397826.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A397826 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A397826/a397826_1.png">Image of the first 10000 terms on the hexagonal spiral</a>. The number colors are graduated across the spectrum, from red to violet, to show their relative size. Small grey lines show the direction of the spiral.
%H A397826 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A397826/a397826_2.png">Image of the first 200000 terms</a>. The colors are graduated across the spectrum from red to violet to show the total number of prime factors of each term, counted with multiplicity. The thin green line is a(n) = n.
%e A397826 The spiral begins:
%e A397826 .
%e A397826           12--37--35--26
%e A397826          /              \
%e A397826        41   23---6--19   33
%e A397826       /    /          \    \
%e A397826     39   10    7---5    8   31
%e A397826    /    /    /      \    \    \
%e A397826  22   29    9    2---3   17   20   .
%e A397826    \    \    \          /    /    .
%e A397826     43   14   11--13---4   27   59
%e A397826       \    \              /    /
%e A397826        47   15--16--21--25   34
%e A397826          \                  /
%e A397826           28--53--55--32--49
%e A397826 .
%e A397826 a(10) = 8 as when a(10) is placed its existing adjacent terms are 3, 5 and 17, and 8 is the smallest unused number that is coprime to all of 3, 5 and 17.
%Y A397826 Cf. A363938 (start with 1), A257339, A396357.
